[7] Democratic Republic of Congo
Date: Mon 15 Jul 2019
Source: Ars Technica [edited]
https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/07/measles-is-killing-more-people-in-the-drc-than-ebola-and-faster/


As the world anxiously monitors the outbreak of Ebola in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), health officials note that a measles outbreak declared last month [June 2019] in the country has killed more people -- mostly children -- and faster.

Since January 2019, officials have recorded over 100 000 measles cases in the DRC, mostly in children, and nearly 2000 have died. The figures surpass those of the latest Ebola outbreak in the country, which has tallied not quite 2500 cases and 1665 deaths since August 2018. The totals were noted by WHO director-general Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus in a speech today, [15 Jul 2019], at the United Nations Office in Geneva, Switzerland.

"Frankly, I am embarrassed to talk only about Ebola," Dr Tedros said. He gave the speech in response to 2 new developments in the Ebola outbreak. That is that 2 Ebola responders were murdered in their home in the DRC city of Beni and that officials on Sun [14 Jul 2019] had identified the 1st case of Ebola in Goma, a DRC city of over one million [people] at the border with Rwanda.

"Both of these events encapsulate the challenges we continue to face on a daily basis in DRC," he said. Tedros was referring to the scattering of disease -- including Ebola and measles -- as violence hampers outbreak responses and access to medical care. Since January [2019], officials have counted 198 attacks on health responders, which left 7 dead and 58 healthcare workers and patients injured.

[byline: Beth Mole]

--
