[8] Israel: vaccination
Date: Mon 15 Jul 2019
From: Dr Eliana M Aaron [edited]


An Israeli expert panel sub-committee recommended vaccinating children with MMR at age 1 and age 2 years to provide an additional booster to this vulnerable age-group. Children ages 1 to 4 years remain the most affected by the measles epidemic.

Routine vaccinations of 6 year olds will continue in school-based clinics. This is in light of an ongoing epidemic in Israel affecting primarily ultra-orthodox Jewish populations and sporadic communities of anti-vaxxers. This epidemic has spread to other ultra-orthodox communities internationally.

The problem with the recommendation is that the Ministry of Health has no budget or staff to implement any additional vaccination programs, and the current public health vaccine clinics are working at maximum capacity. It is estimated that more than 2 million Israelis are unvaccinated or partially vaccinated. The current epidemic has infected 4292 people between 2018 and 11 Jul 2019.

The ultra-orthodox education system is not a public school system, and outsiders, such as government-contracted vaccine clinic nurses, are not admitted. Also, the high number of children per family, lack of easily accessible clinics or mobile vaccine clinics, logistical problems traveling to well-child vaccine clinics (that is, getting on a public bus with 4 or more small children) are all contributing factors towards the low vaccination rates in this population.

Several years ago during a passive polio scare, the community rabbinical leaders were able to encourage over one million ultra-orthodox people to get polio boosters. This leaves us hope that further cooperation and education efforts among community leaders can lead to successful vaccine campaigns.

--
Dr Eliana M Aaron, DNP, APN-BC
Director, EMA Care LLC

******
[9] Israel: vaccination schedule
Date: Mon 15 Jul 2019
Source: Israel Hayom [in Hebrew, trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.israelhayom.co.il/article/674061?utm_source=Facebook&utm_medium


The Committee of Experts on Infectious Diseases recommends that the Ministry of Health advance the 2nd dose of measles vaccine from age 6 years to age 2 years, as a step to fight the disease and prevent the next outbreak.

The experts decided to leave the 1st dose of the vaccine at the age of one year, and not to advance it to the age of 9 months. However, implementation of the recommendation will take several years due to "logistic challenges", as noted by the experts. This means that without the addition of nurse standards and additional budget for vaccinations and the strengthening of the milk drops, the recommendation will not be implemented. Implementation of the recommendation requires the approval of the management of the Ministry of Health.

[byline: Meital Yasur Beit Or]

--
communicated by:
Dr. Eliana M. Aaron, DNP, APN-BC
